In conclusion: this is why I don’t like Belphie. Thank you.

This dream…was a stress dream. It started out as a pleasurable dream about eating a ridiculous amount of cheeseburgers, but quickly turned into a nightmare about Belphie eating him alive due to being disappointed in or angry at him.

Beel has always faded into the background a bit, despite his stature, but when Belphie returns to the main story, he becomes even more entwined with Belphie. You can see how the responsibility he feels for Belphie and for Belphie’s happiness is, literally, eating him alive.

Beel has become dependent on Belphie. No one’s opinions (except probably MC) matter to him except Belphie’s. And he’s overwhelmed and afraid of what will happen if Belphie is left alone. His fears may also reflect his own lack of identity as separate from his twin. https://t.co/vKQp41bvBk

Beel carries the weight of what happened with Belphie long after Belphie is freed from the attic. It’s clear that he is the only one who feels this immense guilt attached to Belphie, likely due to his role as Belphie’s older brother. This need to protect him. But he couldn’t. https://t.co/gWWysvrYNi

Belphie clearly burdened Beel with his emotions and feelings that Beel probably wasn’t ready to handle, or that became overwhelming over time. Let’s not forget that the monster criticizes Beel, putting a burden on him by scolding him about “forgetting” Belphie. https://t.co/Z19LdfiUYb

Beel is feeling so trapped that even the monster gives him a hint. From this, Beel is able to guess that the “monster” that swallowed him was, indeed, his twin brother, Belphegor. This, to me, is VERY telling of the way Beel views his relationship with Belphie. https://t.co/H0WdXSR6ZB

Instead of the game, Beel tries to fight his way out of the situation using his strength. When he can’t, and actually becomes tired from trying, he gets irritated and makes MC play the guessing game instead, frustrated at us when we don’t know the answer either. https://t.co/co2SqSv9me

This is a perfect example of Beel showing traits of autism/other neurodivergency. He knows it’s a game, but it doesn’t follow a logic that he can see, and thus he already feels defeated by it. (I’m autistic and often feel the same, so that’s my credentials here.) https://t.co/9uPqBDh3Oq

Beel is annoyed when the monster insists that Beel guess its name to be let free. From this dialogue, we can see that Beel is smart and logical, but lacks the patience for a guessing game. He’s not going to bother trying to guess an answer he doesn’t know. https://t.co/oEXhrKy5QB
This would be to avoid connecting with us on a deeper level. Regardless, I believe this statement reveals his true feelings. https://t.co/4b4ski0yEq

Beel saves MC from being pickled, even though he admits to liking pickled humans. (My own thoughts on demons eating humans will have to wait.) Despite the…weird phrasing, it’s clear Beel does care about us. He may be trying to convince himself that we are useful to him. https://t.co/SNIegQ8Ua2

I feel like this is where the dream turned into a nightmare. Beel’s pleasurable feast is interrupted without warning by a monster who threatens to (and then later does) swallow him whole. Could indicate Beel’s fears of something he likes becoming dangerous to himself or others. https://t.co/zTtJ2obG2T

This reminds me of binge eating disorders, where a large quantity of food is eaten secretly. I don’t think Beel has an ED, but from this segment and from chats you get from him, it’s clear that, sometimes at least, he views his appetite as something to be ashamed of.

right off the bat, there’s an air of mystery. It feels like Beel is asking for drugs…but it’s cheeseburgers, supposedly made by MC. This could indicate feelings of guilt or shame related to his favorite food, or needing to eat such a large quantity of it in general. https://t.co/DjESv4ytqz
Ended stream a bit pre-maturely due to being sick, but thanks to all who came by! 🥰

Sure, he eats more than any of us could imagine, but he’s a (fictional) demon. I’d say what’s considered a sin as far as Beel is concerned says more about our society than it does about him.

Aside from the few times Beel takes food directly from others, which is often played for comedic effect, and which, I would argue, isn’t that big of a deal, since those characters aren’t starving and could take or find more food elsewhere, the extent of Beel’s sin is eating.

Beel is gluttonous in the way that this fatphobic society views gluttony. But, Beel isn’t gluttonous in the way of the deadly sin. In the rare times when he does feel full, he stops eating. He DOESN’T actively try to be gluttonous, and even talks about holding himself back.

Growing up Christian, I was taught that gluttony as a deadly sin was to desire things (not just food!) in excess. Beel eats a lot, but he’s almost constantly hungry, not to mention that he’s an athlete who works out for hours daily. Athletes eat a lot!

I have a lot of thoughts about Beel and “gluttony,” because while eating “in excess” is typically the “picture” of gluttony as a sin, the truth is that Beel is less gluttonous than certain siblings of his (*cough* Mammon *cough* Asmo *cough*).

The next part of the conversation seems to want you to respond that Beel should eat less, which is stupid, because no one should have to eat less, never mind a demon of gluttony, for crying out loud. It also sounds like the perfect thing to say to someone to give them an ED.

While I think it says a lot about his character, that he is kind and aware of how his sun effects others, food scarcity is something that is created by larger systems like capitalism. Beel could eat all the food restaurants throw out daily and there would still be plenty left!

The anime sometimes seems to mess with the age dynamics, so I’m not sure it can always be relied upon for this analysis. Also, I don’t mean any offense to anyone in any sibling order. I’m an eldest child, so I relate to Beel quite a bit (and Mammon, when he’s responsible.)

Belphie and Asmo give off SERIOUS middle child vibes. They both seem quite self-centered in their own ways, and seem to get away with things relatively easily. Levi and Satan definitely act like the youngest, particularly in the game.

I think Mammon sort of “golden-child”ed his way out of too many responsibilities, since it seems like Lucifer favors him heavily, regardless of what punishment he may or may not inflict on Mammon when he does mess up. But, Mammon does act like an older brother a lot of the time.

Lucifer is the oldest, but is also a “leader” of sorts, and doesn’t seem to deal with everyday squabbles. That role typically falls to Beel, who is the responsible eldest child, and likely carries a lot of the burden that a second born should carry.

So now that we know it’s canon that the brothers weren’t born in the order we are told, that it’s the order of their power level, I would like to posit this birth order:
1. Lucifer
2. Mammon
3. Beel
4. Belphie
5. Asmo
6. Levi
7. Satan

I don’t dislike Genshin. What I do dislike is that the pressure to have a full roster of perfectly built characters is incredibly stressful, and when characters don’t work as well as you’d expect, it can be very depressing. 

DBD doesn’t have that same pressure.

Ringu’s PTB drops soon and I get to decide if I like her playstyle or not. I can choose not to buy her if I want and I can still play DBD as normal.

Genshin used to be like that…but not anymore.

The bloodweb to level a new character is pretty easy to fill up, compared to the hours of grinding needed to play a character at high world levels.

I can go into every match knowing that no matter the build I’m running, I can play all content the same. Not with Genshin.

I may have my critiques of DBD, but I’ll say this much. 

I like that I can run any killer, any survivor, any perk combination, at any time. Even after a new killer gets released. 

I can’t say Genshin Impact is the same way.

And please, I am BEGGING you, be gentle to new players, especially new killers. Because even Doctor has his struggles.

You aren’t going to know where survivors are easily all the time, especially playing killers like Spirit or Wraith. You have to guess a lot of the time, and Doctor’s power does remove that guesswork somewhat. But, do I think people shouldn’t main Doctor? NO. Main who you want!

I have thoughts about who I think new killers should play first. I don’t recommend putting a ton of hours into Doctor until you’ve played another killer first, only because his map pressure is pretty insane. I’d likely say the same for Artist.

I have about 400 hours in the game, and the majority of my killer hours have gone to Spirit. She’s my most reliable killer due in part to her ability, but also my knowledge of her. And yet, I don’t win every game I go into. Survivors are still capable of outplaying me.

Likewise, a beginner Spirit or Doctor isn’t going to be OP right out of the gate. Doctor has amazing map pressure…if the player takes advantage of it. Spirit is an amazing chase killer…if the player can take advantage.

A killer main who spent 1000 hours learning Pig is going to be a menace, even if that person can’t win every game they play. That’s just because they know their killer really well. That’s why a good Nurse player is TERRIFYING.
Man, I think my ~favorite~ thing in the world is people complaining about killers being “too OP.” You wanna know the truth? In the right hands, EVERY killer can be OP.
